  "doc_id": "27276",
  "text": "VEGF expression by luteinized granulosa cells has been demonstrated in vitro with the extent of VEGF mRNA expression differing widely between individual patients [CITATION_1] . Certainly, we observed wide variations in follicular¯uid levels of VEGF in follicles of the same size both in different patients and in the same patient, re¯ecting the unique and individual composition of each follicular environment. What was clear, despite these wide variations, was that the VEGF levels in the follicular¯uid of follicles from the coasted group were consistently lower than in the control group. Whilst [CITATION_2] and [CITATION_3] found increased levels of VEGF in follicular¯uid to be predictive of the development of OHSS, others have found that women at risk of developing OHSS have signi®cantly lower levels of VEGF in follicular¯uid and that lower levels are associated with`good prognosis' patients or hyper-responders [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . It is hypothesized that withholding gonadotrophin reduces the functioning granulosa cell mass available for luteinization with the effect of decreasing any chemical mediators involved in the pathophysiology of OHSS. The lower levels of follicular¯uid VEGF observed in the coasted group may be because gonadotrophin withdrawal has resulted in decreased granulosa cell production of VEGF or may re¯ect the level of follicular¯uid VEGF before coasting since follicular¯uid represents a composite of granulosa cell VEGF secretion over several days and may not entirely be representative of the functional capacity of the granulosa cells at the time of oocyte aspiration. The latter explanation seems more likely since the follicular¯uid VEGF levels in the coasted group are well below those observed in the control group, and our ®ndings therefore would be consistent with those of [CITATION_7] and [CITATION_8] . Coasting undoubtedly has an effect on follicular¯uid VEGF levels with the loss of the correlation between follicle diameter and follicular¯uid VEGF that is observed in the control group. There is also a much wider scatter of follicular¯uid VEGF levels in the coasted group. Coasting probably affects all follicle sizes with differing effects on follicular¯uid VEGF, re¯ecting the unique and individual nature of the follicles which show a variation in their susceptibility to gonadotrophin withdrawal. Interestingly, the type of gonadotrophin used had an impact on the follicular¯uid VEGF concentration in the coasted group, with urinary products having signi®cantly higher follicular¯uid VEGF concentrations. This probably re¯ects the bioavailability of gonadotrophin used during the days of withdrawal of stimulation and may imply that urinary products would be better used in women suspected to be at high risk of OHSS. This aspect needs further evaluation.",
